PROJETO-DE-PESQUISA.NOME-DO-PROJETO: Protocolos para avaliação pré-cirurgia ortognática de análises cinemática e eletromiográfica
PROJETO-DE-PESQUISA.DESCRICAO-DO-PROJETO: A análise tridimensional dos movimentos mandibulares, faciais e a eletromiografia de superfície são instrumentos importantes para a descrição das funções e dos processos de adaptação. &#10;Objetivo: O objetivo deste projeto é de caracterizar e analisar os dados objetivos registrados e integrados por meio de Eletromiografia de Superfície dos músculos mastigatórios, da análise optoeletrônica tridimensional da funcionalidade da articulação temporomandibular, dos movimentos faciais e da produção da fala, durante a realização de tarefas estáticas e dinâmicas padronizadas, por sujeitos saudáveis (grupo controle) e indivíduos afetados por diferentes Deformidades Dentofaciais (DDF) (Classes II e III) candidatos ao intervento de Cirurgia Ortognática.&#10;Método: Participarão do estudo 80 sujeitos, entre 18 e 40 anos, de ambos os gêneros divididos em dois grupos. O grupo I será constituído com 40 sujeitos portadores de DDF Classe II ou Classe III de Angle que procurarem tratamento no Centro Integrado de Estudos das Deformidades da Face (CIEDEF) do Hospital das Clínicas da Faculdade de Medicina de Ribeirão Preto da Universidade de São Paulo (HC-FMRP-USP). O grupo II (controle) será constituído com mais 40 indivíduos Classe I de Angle e que não apresentem qualquer alteração da motricidade ou sensibilidade da face. Este grupo será composto por voluntários, dentre eles, colegas e familiares. Todos os indivíduos serão submetidos à avaliação fonoaudiológica que consiste na avaliação clínica miofuncional orofacial, avaliação da atividade e da coordenação muscular por meio do eletromiógrafo BTS FREEEMG, a análise da cinemática mandibular, dos movimentos faciais e da produção da fala, por meio do sistema optoeletrônico BTS SMART, ambos da BTS Bioengineering Company (S.p.a, Garbagnate Milanese, Italy) (obtidos com recursos do Programa de Incentivo à Pesquisa da Reitoria da Universidade de São Paulo).

PROJETO-DE-PESQUISA.NOME-DO-PROJETO: Quantitative analysis of the facial and speech movements through optoelectronic motion analysis and surface electromyography
PROJETO-DE-PESQUISA.DESCRICAO-DO-PROJETO: Functional impairments of facial movements alter the quality of life, and their quantitative analysis is a key step in the description and grading of facial function and dysfunction. In this investigation we assessed the symmetry of lip movements in verbal and non-verbal movements in healthy subjects.&#10;A non-invasive recording protocol, integrating an electromyographic system and an optoelectronic 3D-motion analyzer, has been developed and used to detect lip movements in verbal and non-verbal movements.&#10;Two separate investigations have been made. In the first study, functional symmetries of the lip movements were assessed in a control group of clinically healthy subjects. Data were evaluated separately for men and women, and a gender-related effect was tested.&#10;The aim of the second study was to assess the onset of the EMG activity of zygomaticus and depressor labii inferioris muscles that play a role in speech pronunciation and smiling movements.&#10;The outcomes suggest that the proposed method could be a useful tool to evaluate the asymmetry of the lips and of the facial muscles during the performance of smiling, lip purse and speech pronunciation, and to detect functionally altered facial conditions.

DADOS-BASICOS-DO-ARTIGO.TITULO-DO-ARTIGO-INGLES: Electromyographic standardized indices in healthy Brazilian young adults and data reproducibility

INFORMACOES-ADICIONAIS.DESCRICAO-INFORMACOES-ADICIONAIS: Abstract &#10;The determination of normal parameters is an important procedure in the evaluation of the stomatognathic system. We used the surface electromyography standardization protocol described by Ferrario et al. (J Oral Rehabil. 2000;27:33-40, 2006;33:341-8) to determine reference values of the electromyographic standardized indices for the assessment of muscular symmetry (left and right side, percentage overlapping coefficient, POC), potential lateral displacing components (unbalanced contractile activities of contralateral masseter and temporalis muscles, TORS), relative activity (most prevalent pair of masticatory muscles, ATTIV), and total activity (integrated areas of the electromyographic potentials over time, IMPACT), in healthy Brazilian young adults, and the relevant data reproducibility. Electromyography of the right and left masseter and temporalis muscles was performed during maximum teeth clenching in 20 healthy subjects (10 women, 10 men, mean age 23 years, SD 3), free from periodontal problems, temporomandibular disorders, orofacial myofunctional disorder, and with full permanent dentition (28 teeth at least). Data reproducibility was computed for 75% of the sample. The values obtained were POC Temporal (88.11±1.45%), POC Masseter (87.11±1.60%), TORS (8.79±1.20%), ATTIV (-0.33±9.65%), IMPACT (110.40±23.69 µV/µVs %). There were no statistical differences between test and retest values (p>0.05). The Technical Errors of Measurement for 50% of subjects assessed during the same session were 1.5, 1.39, 1.06, 3.83, 10.04. For 25% of the subjects assessed after a 6-month interval the Technical Errors of Measurement were 0.80, 1.03, 0.73, 12.70, 19.10. For all indices, there was good reproducibility. These electromyographic indices could be used in the assessment of patients with stomatognathic dysfunction.

INFORMACOES-ADICIONAIS.DESCRICAO-INFORMACOES-ADICIONAIS: Mandibular kinematic and standardized surface electromyography (sEMG) characteristics of masticatory muscles of subjects with short lasting TMD of mild-moderate severity were examined. &#10;Volunteers were submitted to clinical examination and questionnaire of severity. Ten subjects with TMD (age 27.3 years, SD 7.8) and 10 control subjects without TMD, matched by age, were selected.&#10;Mandibular movements were recorded during free maximum mouth opening and closing (O-C) and unilateral, left and right, gum chewing. sEMG of the masseter and temporal muscles was performed during maximum teeth clenching either on cotton rolls or in intercuspal position, and during gum chewing. sEMG indices were obtained. Subjects with TMD, relative to control subjects, had lower relative mandibular rotation at the end of mouth opening, larger mean number of intersection between interincisal O-C paths during mastication and smaller asymmetry between working and balancing side, with participation beyond the expected of the contralateral muscles (p<0.05, t-test). Overall, TMD subjects showed similarities with the control subjects in several kinematic parameters and the EMG indices of the static test, although some changes in the mastication were observed.
